Last-minute duel: MP3 players against mobile phones
We will recommend how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
From this it is clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why you should be able to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy yourself an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LP and from a qualitative point of view there is not even an objective reason for this.
If, however, hard-rock, jazz or blues are crowded on your shelves, you probably dream about a turntable like this.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend 8,000 crowns on a reader, as well as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the twenty crowns of the market.
Two extremes of which there's enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is decided.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but they don't do cell phones by mistake.
There is no other device as universal as the mobile phone.
Next to the primary functions, telephone and text, he can read music and video, record both and he has a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe he can even navigate.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds, you'll also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle since no refrigerator can make a grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and before the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than 12 hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As far as cheap phones are concerned, you don't count on them to last for more than a few hours.
If you still add, from time to time, some calls, get work for safety another charger, this also applies to the most expensive devices.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst will last a minimum of 9 hours with continuous functionality with a refill.
Another problem is when you download music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately only a limited part of devices has the universal USB port and in addition not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Certainly the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory readers are able to make it without adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for a few exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a multimedia library ordered according to the names of the performers, name of the album, genre or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the tree structure of folders, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both (iver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When choosing a particular device, be particularly interested in battery resistance, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs, and clearly ease of use.
If the music is mainly for the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram, you just need an ordinary MP3 phone.
This happens now, clearly to any cell phone.
You don't have to worry too much about which formats your mobile phone or reader recognize.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be right in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular ones, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
It is located less than the AAC (format used by Apple and its Ipod companies).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet network, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another supplier) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument to buy a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is poor and is usually limited only to hits of radio time.
The prices aren't exactly low.
But it is generally assumed that this method of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little something goes through their pocket while the MP3 player is left at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry your headphones or at least the wireless headset.
If not, you can use the integrated player that almost every mobile phone, but only a small part of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheaper ones normally cost less than 3,000 kronor.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an entrance for common headphones.
The best and technically most equipped mobile phones and even with 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
The advantage of readers is, in addition to others, easy handling.
The simplest ones not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) can really handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of handling once with the common stereo or even the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally hitting the start-up of the mobile internet network and consequently of a giant bill for data transmission.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, you return to the 2 000 kronor.
But be careful.
Base models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones make it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iliver.
According to the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are among the most demanding listeners, please take the specialist mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have individual keys for MP3 and the convenience of the service so it gets closer to the same MP3 player.
In this context, Sony Ericsson has made more progress, which walkman cell phones have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above mentioned brands ensure the same service and price category up to 4 000 kronor, but with a larger storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery resistance (commonly 15 hours, generally up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as of this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is mature enough and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
There is something missing here - a virtual operator who forces traditional operators to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe has already been written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, it was also confirmed by Mr Čti, who pointed out that the price of SMS is higher for us than for the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS messages will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high for Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds crazy, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly over 100%.
Instead, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecoms Council (ČTře), Pavel Dvořák, who has sometimes expressed that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic, also often stresses.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network no longer probably has many possibilities. (Moreover, perhaps it would be difficult to find other frequencies by now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that led to a significant fall in prices, to which traditional operators would then have to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, there were similar voices in Britain as we did.
However, it has been shown that there is a place for such operators and that they can be really successful.
At the end of the day, for example, we must not go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual mobile operator in Poland.
In only half a year this operator managed to conceive more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking lies the financial group Penta to which in the Czech Republic belongs among other things U: fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to operate effectively, that is to say, it is sufficient to have many fewer customers than to a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them, that is, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
So for example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS messages that cost at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows it can be a pretty good move even the bet on a target group not a little.
This operator points specifically to men, so to speak.
"Real men choose Mobilking operator that they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we too can affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
Press spokesperson for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubted: "The Czech market is relatively small due to a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover from the point of view of the services is relatively saturated. "
In the Czech Republic no possibility, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic, Mobilking will not be.
"There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but negotiations in the Czech Republic do not have much expectations.
Mobilking will be switched on rather in the other countries of our area, "he said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman of the Penta financial group.
Thus, it indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this thinking.
On the contrary, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor can be created.
For some time now, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, GTS Novera, who would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to make progress in negotiations with some of them, "says Pavel Kaidl Group spokesperson.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator will probably have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, an impenetrable wall of silence stands around its creation.
"At this moment we do not believe that in the Czech market there is room for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far no subject with a complex and serious project has turned to us, "he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršei of the Telefònika O2 press section.
Other operators also rely on the specificity of the Czech market.
Press spokesperson for T-Mobil Martina Kemrová added in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any viable and mutually beneficial commercial project, on which it is possible to continue to build."
He adds: "A virtual operator will hardly appear in the T-Mobil network by the end of the year.
At this moment we already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon. "
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on reaching its 3G licence requests.
Miroslav Čepický added: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet. "
The competent authorities - with the accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can easily be understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to lower profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances around the creation U: fon testify that when operators care about something they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure was pressing on ČTři during the period of creation of U: fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This testifies to public access information from ČTři's web pages.
But now just U: fon serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has been underdeveloped with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Regarding the typology of the mobile market in the Czech Republic it is obvious that the entrance of another competitor would place on him and above all on his high demands services. "
However, the attitude of the mobile operators is surprising because of the total lack of interest on the part of the Czech regulators.
This is not just about the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately has no competence to interfere in economic competition in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
"The virtual operator's entry into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had materialised.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators, "said Kristián Chalupa, of the External Relations Section ÚOHS, in reply to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators is perhaps not surprising.
On the other hand, on the part of the office, which must defend the interests of consumers and also deal with the fact that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, it is more than a delicate matter.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators commonly operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not, of course, belong to the interests of ÚOHS.
The almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions is truly striking throughout the situation.
The question of whether it's really just a coincidence is on its own.
Similarly, the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations is the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no signs of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecoms regulator, "said Mr Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
There is, of course, an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTřís, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - the network operator's agreement is always necessary for the creation of a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator has - logically at the end of the day - the monopoly of his network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant.
But even if we do not accept this argument, it should be a bit alerting for ÚOHS that three mobile operators proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to ČTři in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS keeps itself out of the whole thing.
We have already found this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to promote the expansion of ČTři's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently passed telecoms law was updated, despite the fact that, from this, many experts expected the situation to improve.
This fact the representatives of ÚOHS must know more than well, but perhaps their interests lie elsewhere.
It can be done when no one looks.
While without us noticing, the functioning of these pseudo-virtual operators remains, of which there are even some in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that publish their price lists of mobile phone services but are only partially public.
Usually they are companies dealing with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only the predetermined persons.
The magic lies in the fact that the company vis-à-vis the operator appears as a classic corporate customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a pre-sale.
"If the cases mentioned, of which we are going to intervene, were presented, this could be a breach of contractual conditions and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with that company," replied Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity would reach the ears of those responsible for mobile operators.
Especially in the cases of the 3 companies mentioned, this can be done by thousands of customers.
No operator defends himself at the same time from such an attitude.
In other words, they derive a considerable profit from the activities of these companies and at the same time - unlike real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way by their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot dispose in full of it as the usual customers of mobile operators. "
But this should be a bit odd at the ČTří.
In addition, another issue for ÚOHS opens up.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why are they blocking the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanation of operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant fall in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small market, too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in the developed countries, in these very cases, regulatory bodies have intervened in defence not of mobile operators but of their customers.
Both formal measures and non-formal pressure have led to the creation of the first virtual operator and others have joined him.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw themselves from one to the other the whole case like a hot potato.
In our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes it more than convenient.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator will appear really soon from us, the Czech mobile market will start again.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it would be difficult for ÚOHS to remain unaffected by the refusal (discrimination) of the other parties concerned.
And we might stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a solemn manner the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj."
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - solo with male or female voice, chorus pitch and instrumental edition.
The song is directed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the review of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already earlier he said on the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing variants to solo, singers with the most representative young voices, which are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and even the choir, have a clear diction, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he said.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year's 175-year anniversary.
The song "Kde domov můj" was played for the first time in 1834 on stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in the original opera Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
He gained popularity and people spontaneously made him his own.
The first verse of the song after the foundation of Czechoslovakia in 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
