Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly of Florida: only six miles from the center of Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
It's 90% black today.
The outsiders who come to look for the story of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permission requested in advance is required for most interviews, to some things - such as the murals on the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by a white man, who show black men in the fields - do not have permission to be photographed.
