The German Günther Bauer in "Flamenco-People" alternates the theatre of some shots to singers, dancers and guitarists on stage with the less well-known side of these masters.
With this objective, the photographer offers an original iconography of flamenco, capturing it from different visual angles.
The exhibition, included in the programming of the Month of Flamenco Photography, reflects the international importance of this dance, every day increasing, "explains the artist and clarifies that in" Flamenco-People "may also be ordinary people, but seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists, performers on the scene.
These people portrayed "on the street" are "artists able to convey passion, sadness, joy when they are on stage... and to capture the audience.
In order to capture the personality of these great ones, it is not necessary to portray them on stage,
because their personality and character are interior.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the great flamenco. "
With a passion for the festival "Cante de las Minas," Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray singers, guitarists or dancers using a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the type of machine and the material, recall classical photography.
The application of different stylistic techniques breaks with the traditional principles of the image, giving to the modern photo, according to an idea that reflects the conception of the flamenco proper to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and is able to surprise every day."
Not dancing, singing or playing in itself, but the artist's personality, his character, capable of conquering the audience with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential elements, with the magic that becomes visible in a certain way of feeling and being, are and have been the constant of this work, on display these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Famous flamenco artists such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are included in this selection of about seventy artists portrayed.
