The Ministry of the Interior requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol levels install in their car the system that prevents the driving of the vehicle in a drunken state or if they do not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Public Prosecutor's Office, according to which it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since he will have to attend a road rehabilitation course.
In addition to the Attorney General for Road Safety, the Directorate General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico per la Sicurezza dell'Automobile (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once per DUI then returned to driving the car.
Alcohol would avoid this, because it is a vehicle-related system that measures the alcohol rate in the expired air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher alcohol concentration is detected than allowed.
The cost is more than EUR 1000 and would be borne by the sanction.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles fitted with such devices allow for a reduction of up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it's estimated that it could save 115 people's lives a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviour before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, and, without doubt, the reform necessary for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced on an experimental basis in some industrial and public vehicles.
