Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak while falling asleep.
The first time that happens, at most you take a scare, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquy.
It appears with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in a lifetime, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with a greater regularity (every day, once a week, once in the month...), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes they are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nocturnal fears, night enuresis (peeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above it may be associated with very high fever stages, stress or over-recitation situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon that is still little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks in a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to see if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet for the situation.
We have said that it is a benign alteration therefore there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, when coupled with insomnia or stress).
What can be done, however, is to consider a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid TV programs or series that raise fear or suggest violence.
