The meeting - The blood is safe again
The Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, since the Héma-Québec has become one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years 1980 to 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected by the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus in the 1980s.
In the face of such a tragedy and the protests of the population, the Canadian Government conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances which led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee to design a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Society of Blood for all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still had faith in the system of donations in Québec, Dr Décary recalls.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research in the following years, we have regained public confidence, "he explains before saying proud that at the beginning of 2008, around 94% of the population of Quebec had confidence in Héma-Quebec.
However, Dr Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, the Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, many cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, were seen in Europe, telling the president of the disease since 1998, the year of its foundation.
"And we had absolutely no idea if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports was that when doubts arise and a serious illness could arise, in this case, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself as degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, should be excluded.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years now, it has been shown that this disease is without doubt transmitted through infected blood.
This episode showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle. "
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (TAN) that allow direct recognition of the presence of the virus and not of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
The TAN have reduced the window period, that is from the moment the person contracted the disease to the moment when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and not being able to detect them has therefore decreased considerably.
These improvements have considerably reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with the HIV virus.
"In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted by transfusion occurs.
I believe that today we can feel at ease in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health, says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikunga virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant, "continues Dr Décary before pointing out that apart from having secure resources, the Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Needs increase as the population gets older.
As cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the number of donors that on average make up only 3% of the inhabitants of Quebec acceptable as donors. "
However, all healthy persons who are 18 years of age and meet the eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people offering as donors are not accepted because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where it is widespread, they will be refused for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
There are very rare cases of shortage.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they get older and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and to encourage them to become regular donors.
Nowadays, life is so hectic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood, "Francine Décary says desolate.
With an annual budget of 297 million dollars, the Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, of which bone transplants, ocular globus heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited with the Héma-Québec which manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds rich blood of stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion into the bank of our thousandth sample of cordon blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
We should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year, "says Dr Décary, who describes this practice of cordon blood collection as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because the Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals of Quebec.
