Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to stand up against his position.
No matter the outcome of the trial, the writers and the publisher of the book Canada Black will have to spend a large amount of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from the practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these unequal-armed struggles, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that will gag the opposition as well as frighten anyone who dares to give a fresh ruling on the matter.
