Operation - Rescue for Wall Street - Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, representatives of the Republican and Democratic side, finally came to an agreement yesterday on the largest rescue-finance plan after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan, which aims to put a brake on the financial crisis that has been hanging over Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
It provides, in particular, for checks on its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of foreclosed houses for non-payments, as well as a right of inspection of remuneration paid to managers of protected undertakings.
American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great progress towards an effective market agreement," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Every decision has been taken in such a way as to safeguard the economy and the American people from the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the crucial point: if we had not acted in this way, priceless disappointments and upheavals would have poured into the daily lives of Americans," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new bankruptcy on investors.
The time limit allowed was the opening of markets this morning.
Together with the negotiations later, the two candidates for the American presidential elections were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction at the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves the credit for adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow the owners to keep their home and the one concerning the remuneration for managers of state-funded companies.
"When asking taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to be welcomed about.
But these measures are necessary, "he commented on the American TV screen.
Interviewed on another channel to know if he will vote in favour of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"According to what I read, this is something that we all need to digest and that will allow us to move forward."
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable, "he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the dubious credits, the assets at risk and unsaleable of the American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the outbreak of a real estate bubble that led first to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (mortgages), then to other more widespread forms of debt securities (PCAA) and leading to the freezing of liquidity and the downside of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of incumbent Republicans who blew up the first draft agreement last week.
It seems to have come out of that dead end since the Democrats agreed that the "toxic" assets of some companies in difficulty are only protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone in Congress, a provision has been added that if the government were to face losses over the next five years as a result of this programme, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which a further 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion should be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the protected companies that will be worth the dividends in case of profit and that will be able to sell back when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the Federal Government will have the opportunity to delay the foreclosure procedures relating to real estate loans and to set limits on the remuneration and starting-up allowances paid to the managers of the undertakings concerned.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit him to the vote of the House of Representatives, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will be given the green light.
In fact, yesterday there were several votes against the project, both on the Republican and democratic sides.
"Evidently, Washington can't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's Finance Committee, to his voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not to take advantage of the taxpayers.
Leader of a small group in Congress nicknamed "the Skeptical Caucus," democratic representative Brad Sherman presents the situation differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economic professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written to us to say: we ask Congress not to draw hasty conclusions and to examine carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis in Europe.
