What was produced in the Zuschlag & member invoice factory?
The hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and members will be discussed shortly on 8 October.
The politician and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed in the context of a criminal association that has caused considerable damage, and of other crimes, including falsification of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money obtained from notices of competition has been used by them for private purposes, and they have often certified the carrying out of the activities through false invoices.
The state and municipal money, a total of 65 million guilders, ended up partly in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, made known by the investigating authorities, they withdrew the money obtained from notices of competition on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and associations have never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were false.
To make them, the blocks of invoices were purchased at the Józsefváros market, the circular stamps instead were manufactured at Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which companies to issue invoices, it was established inter alia during the trip between the hills above the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession, he had to choose pensions and restaurants.
He asked for invoices for consumption, on the model of these then were prepared invoices to be forwarded to the notices of competition, among others, to those of the Ministry for Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the City of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András Mauri, who, according to our information, drew up the reports needed to obtain the funding.
One of the choices of Lados's "study trip" was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and its members in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
So many people, however, according to the restaurateur, would not all enter the restaurant together.
Similarly, the bill issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, is full of errors of form and content.
A Badacsonytomaj guesthouse has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay overnight, however 130 guests were included in the invoice.
But the fictitious invoice compilers went too far when they reported Pigal Kft., which also deals with catering, in whose accounts - according to the information given to the judicial authorities - the documents on behalf of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá were not even included.
Győző Farkas, the company's administrator, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the Public Prosecutor's Office and showed him the invoices, he immediately understood that they were false documents.
"On the stamp the name and the VAT game of our company were at a wrong point."
He added: in addition to the formal reasons, the fact that according to the invoice 100 people were accommodated, when in total they have eleven rooms and there are not so many beds.
In addition, the invoice was catering and their restaurant has not been in operation for a long time.
The assiduous invoice compilers did not bother to inform themselves that the travel agency in Budapest of their choice, only organizes trips abroad, so they shocked indicated on the invoice with cash payment trips to Hungary, which did not agree with the company's practice of issuing invoices.
In addition, as demonstrated during the investigation, VAT was included on the invoice, while the activity of travel to countries outside the European Union is exempt VAT.
Among other things the amount of VAT was also wrong on the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favor of the foundation Jobb Jövőért, in fact on the services offered by the company it is necessary to apply the VAT to 15% and not to 25% as indicated on the invoices, moreover the employees of the hotel issued only printed invoices, while the invoice produced was written by hand.
In addition to this, the "broadcasters" have ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they have indicated as carried out activity goods by road, as is known from the procedure of the Public Prosecutor, activity that was not carried out from the company founded originally for advice of investments.
Moreover for formal defects - due to non-compliant invoice format, false stamp - it has been discovered that invoices issued in favor of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false.
The same happened in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the sports ground of Kunfehértó, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The counterfeiters did not even pay attention to the fact that the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület had lunch there, precisely for this reason the liquidator of the company, according to our information, denied having issued that invoice.
They've issued invoices knowingly.
Another group of invoice issuers consists of those who were aware of having to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták in favour of the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért of nearly 4 million florins.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the indictment, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
He also collaborated with Zuschlag and members of Biogate Kft currently in liquidation, which in 2003 provided invoices issued for a value of about 5 million florins to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, behind which there was no real economic activity.
Not even movement of money because the prepared invoices were then turned away, but the associations forgot to make this aspect appear in their own documents.
In the following group of companies issuing invoices belong those who can be connected with the accused.
For example Ivan Kubatov, authorised to direct the Director General of the Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, who deals with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 relating to the sale of computer equipment, for a value of approximately 18 million guilders.
According to the investigation, the Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas under liquidation since 14 September 2005 purchased these invoices.
The director general of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov would forward documents concerning the company between 2002 and 2005.
According to us Kubatov, during the investigation, he acknowledged that he had issued invoices on behalf of the company to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the countervalue was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov Romanian masons founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of the companies were operational, because according to the defendant, they had not received a job.
However, the companies returned useful because at the request of the co-defendant lawyer Zsolt Szente, editor of the founding documents of the companies, invoices were issued in the name of the companies to the associations related to Zuschlag: to the Atlasz and the Y-Generáció.
On behalf of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade Kubatov has issued 15 invoices to the various entities for a total value of 14,2 million florins.
The Prosecutor considers that Kubatov has cashed 10% of the amounts shown on the invoices, as well as VAT.
The man also used the Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, manufactured for Biztos Pont's competition notice.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 presented a call for the public benefit agency of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 guilders each but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the ban.
In order to avoid this, they submitted to TMA five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These invoices were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants, as they have already done in the public prosecutor's office, are likely to report on the trend in the production of invoices.
However, the most interesting thing might be if the defendant number one, János Zuschlag, decided to lift the veil on everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and even though he has promised several times to talk about everything in an extensive way, he has not yet done so.
We have to see if it is in your interest, it may also be that the socialists have reached agreements with Zusi, who - in exchange for compensation of 50 million guilders, much of the damage - would be prepared to be a scapegoat.
Zuschlag could have been offended for now, as his demands for the relief of his prison conditions, namely the granting of house arrest, have not been met so far.
While the perpetrators of non-reparable commercial crimes and causing much greater damage can freely walk or at least wait at home for the end of the proceedings against them, which is not granted to him.
The Psychology of Excess Licencing: Why Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers are inclined to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and economists researchers from the University of New York managed to discover the neuro-economic basis of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study in Science magazine men do not want to stay behind in a race such as the eBay auction, so they are also willing to pay a higher price.
Research has tried to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers played the lot, the other group of players participated in an auction while with the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) they examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to fire more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex enters intensively into operation when you lose to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
So according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by the vehemently dodging the reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group carried out a financial pursuit investigation.
In this investigation, three groups fired against one partner under different conditions.
To the control group they reported what the real value of the product in question was and they made their bet.
To another group in addition to this they promised that in the event of winning they will receive another prize of $15.
The third group would have received 15 dollars before the auction, but the members of the group would have lost the money in the event of a loss at auction.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was underlined, while for the other the loss.
By proving neurologists' hypothesis, members of the group that played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winning."
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These, in fact, have so far explained the phenomena that can be found at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image have helped to resolve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we have reached a third explanation, "said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to seek medical attention?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, whereas in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as the first cause of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis sufferers is one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver disease caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g. water and infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leaks, saliva).
It is useful for travellers to vaccinate against the virus A and B, against the C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
Then yellowish spots form on the skin and whites of the eyes, the faeces become clear and dark urine, healing occurs within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is estimated to be that only one in ten people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumours.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens subtly destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical analyses.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed people.
In the world today, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease it is worth calling the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is treatable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infective power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by patient associations.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University performed an interesting experiment, examining the way faith in God affects the feeling of pain, British Telegraph reported.
In the context of the rather bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out to 12 Catholic believers and to as many atheists, while all were observing a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to repel much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploratory technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for the control of pain.
The test is the first in a series of research in which scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University take part as well as academics.
The test was carried out exactly like this: a tool that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with the hermine by Leonardo da Vinci painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary would originate a kind of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and considered it to be a tranquilizing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time they received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe," as if "someone took care" of them and "were calm and pervaded by peace."
Looking at the religious image, they accounted for 12% less pain than when Leonardo's work was before them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but it is necessary to find the appropriate image.
"We need to look for an image to which they have very positive feelings, such as a mother or father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the result of the search.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality." - added Wright.
After the excellent results there is only the question whether a painting of a madonna by Leonardo or another painter of such caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You're what you say about yourself
On the day of the tenth birthday Google can claim to be both in people's pockets and in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which clinic they attend and what interests them.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's directors, this is not enough.
What concerns the skeptics who make a comparison with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see exactly the substance of the web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as much personal data as its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google's founders who was: "We put all the world's information into a system!."
According to the director of Google interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to manage all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years' time Schmidt answered: he would like if Google could answer questions like "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?," but the software doesn't know how to answer apparently simple questions because they don't know enough about users.
Not all internet users are aware that during their searches on the internet, exactly the words you search for are recorded, from which IP address you search and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
By means of the Personalized Search started two years ago users e.g. can store their browsing history, they can relate to what they have searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailor-made results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services according to our preferences declared and recorded previously.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - the concerned users of Google's data monopoly wonder.
In most cases, the counter-reactions of the internauti are caused by the fear felt for the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not for the guilt, for the fear of punishment, for the desire for freedom or even for the rebellion in power.
One fact is confirmed, however, that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against paedophiles in Brazil, in which Google forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that made it possible to identify paedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internauti worried about personal rights instead sighed of relief in May when the company - in agreement with the association of electronic legal protection EFF - successfully demonstrated the truth in court against the FBI: not even later can Google be forced with no point in the constitution to provide any information requested secretly by the FBI.
