The intelligent machine mimics the flight of the hornet
What would be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies if not to mimic the sensors of obstacles found in nature?
Bees, for example.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, hornets gave the initial strategic inspiration to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-car equipped with the properties of bees, with the ultimate aim of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying the bees form an own oval personal space that really looks much like our protective shield - it has explained to the Kazuhiro exhibition Doi, director of the field technologies PR and research and development.
Important is the role of the view of the bee, capable of a view of 300 degrees in each direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetry laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction turning the wheels of the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance manoeuvre, in a different way from the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robot car would not be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the auto robot project.
It must react in an instinctive and immediate way because this technology corresponds to the damaging and inner layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering wheels.
In this way instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their life is longer than those to lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneity of intelligent reaction is important, not data processing or even less the ability to store it.
This robot has to process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to memorize and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so it uses only a memory of a few tens of Kb.
You don't need a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that, they predict to Nissan, can be installed in standard vehicles within 10 years.
Further possibilities of application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system that avoiding the obstacles present on the road leads to destination.
