Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today in Paris the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun, organized this year by France with the rotating presidency of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz of the European People's Party in the message addressed to the plenum as main rapporteur of the Congress drew attention to school segregation because it is the most serious legal violation affecting Roma children and also the most serious obstacle to their assertion.
Mr Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Mr Vladimír Špidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities, opened the conference at the highest level.
Among those invited to the conference were governments, European social partners and representatives of major European civil and rights organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
Mr Járóka, according to the Press Office of the Parliamentary Group Fidesz EP, recalled, in addition to discrimination in recruitment, that Roma are being excluded from the labour market primarily because of their low schooling.
"Most young Roma do not have an average level of education and as a result of poor quality primary education only a small number of them can achieve a higher level of education."
Mr Járóka also stressed, as a fundamental human right, the key role of education in upholding human rights.
Investing in the education of Roma children can mean strengthening the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
In her view, it is necessary to make these links more aware in the wider context between the Roma and non-Roma.
In fact, the sooner a Roma school starts, the more its chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market grow; through taxes paid for income and consumption they contribute to the nation's budget.
"The right of European citizenship of the Roma must guarantee their right to quality education and the elimination of low-level and segregated schools" - stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the MP, the union of purpose and action of the European Union is necessary in order to accelerate the processes of desegregation of schools and for this reason it is of fundamental importance that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives be respected.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be interrupted, Roma children must be given the opportunities provided by the democratic space so that they can contribute fully to the future of Europe," Járóka asked.
In the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" to be guaranteed for all, the aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organised each year, since the Berlin meeting last year is to ensure a single forum to promote the objectives of anti-discrimination and equal opportunities set at the state and European level.
