The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the rescue plan of 700 billion dollars launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
Yesterday's New York Times confirms this by informing us that the current crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and business community, and its new soul, conservative, hostile to "Washington's" and the world of finance, strong especially in the States of Central and South.
The soul, in fact, that became prepoterously alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This is, however, just an example of the changes, of the major changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps anticipates or already shows: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe the crisis seems to act as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time and in the new climate they solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereignty in relation to a sort of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, yes, have strong links with foreign countries, but which, first and foremost, see the budgets of people and families living in one country, one state involved to a very large extent.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically world-wide but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems fundamentally out of the question or not to have much to say: the clear evidence is given by the European Union which, as usual, is divided between the different interests and between the different state strategies, fails to decide any common policy line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all disbursement of funds: since when it comes to the straits it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back on track.
And they also possess the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market and no international organization will be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the national-state element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely related to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we have now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalised finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to deal to an increasing extent with those very little intangible things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look at it, can certainly be transported from one place to the other of the earth but are however absolutely linked to a limited space, to a territory.
So that those who find themselves sovereign, certainly possess several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second innovation, but it is a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the demand of someone who knows how to take matters into his own hands.
On the other hand, there is a wave of discredit for existing leadership, especially economic leadership, which has proved to be so inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And at the same time something even deeper and somewhat disturbing: a discredit, a lack of suffering, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of countries in the West.
In other words, it seems to be becoming more and more clear, in large sections of the population, that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far in auge, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall meaning of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, undermines a ramified but powerful movement of delegation of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "uprisings" or in the sudden turns of the collective moods of these last and last times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Great Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rituals, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape in the deep layers of Western societies today and that the economic crisis reinvigorates, increases, acts potentially out of proportion.
Faced with all this talk of a "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not.
