Historical cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes."
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the great Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of the great multisales and the consequent death by consunction of the monosal in the central areas of the cities, is one of those events that appear ineluctable and incontrovertible to us but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
They are often places of history and memory, "it is as if a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of road and many emotions," says the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornatore the Oscar Award and the Grand Prix of the Cannes jury, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall and nostalgia for a way of living the lost cinema perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of exhibitors, speak clearly: in the last five years 316 traditional films have been closed, and above all the main cities pay the highest price: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost single-screen cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multiplex cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures but we should ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its visitors are willing to move into multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund for exhibitors: the state's past debt is around EUR 10 million.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year. "
Interesting the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, has decided to run to the shelter with the signature of a protocol between Municipality and Anec, the first of this type in Italy, in order to protect and promote the monosal cinemas both in the historical center and in the suburbs.
Among the rules envisaged are tax relief measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special parking rates and in some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like," notes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counteract the extravagance of multiplexes, traditional rooms must also improve the quality of sound and image, because the audience today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to do "New cinema Paradiso," to which I have been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass in front of the Rialto or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the billboards blackened by the dust I turn on the other side. "
