When the energy comes from the waves now the big ones come down into the field
It is an exterminated field, which occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface, and now the world's largest energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have put their eyes, and now they are trying to get their hands on, giant like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for 100 years and in the 70's, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, the research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now the environmental demands and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by sea wave exploitation plants.
This amount would be twice as much as that currently produced by nuclear power stations.
Plus there would be currents and tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years later, betting on marine energy is becoming more and more and among these companies that have always been devoted to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying the technologies on the oceanic energy - the spokesman of a company associated to the American oil giant to the economic daily Wall Street Journal has declared - and is considering the possibility to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
This is not a small signal, especially considering that the US is still extracting oil in Alaska and President Bush has recently launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to the Chevron, there are the Verdant Power Inc. of New York and the Ocean Power of New Jersey to travel the path of energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, indicate according to the observers an increasing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about technology still in its infancy, not least because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese plant or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
However, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used to produce large-scale energy.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine that, in turn, feeds a generator.
The electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type being designed, waiting only for federal approval and some of the energy could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping center and parking space using six underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of the water when there are tides turns the turbine blades, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Research of Electricity, deserves the potential of tides at the moment.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like that of New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that overlook the coasts, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and planned investments up to 35 million for 2009.
